<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-03-10T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-03-10T07:00:00-05:00" n="305" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d305">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">800.91293/16: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-10T19:00:00+07:00">March 10,
                                1944—7 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received March 11—11:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>456. Minister of Information H. C. Liang informed foreign correspondents at
                        press conference March 8 that while date of trip to Yenan had not yet been
                        set they would probably leave “within a month.” Liang stated correspondents
                        would proceed from Chungking to Sian, thence to Yenan and Ninghsia and
                        added, in reply to question, itinerary might include Chinghai but not
                        Sinkiang. At press conference previous week, Liang said trip would last 5 or
                        6 months.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>